# [TLS](../wg/tls.html)

## Summary

The TLS Working Group (WG) held its first of two sessions at IETF 125. The session focused on the progression of post-quantum cryptography (PQC) integration into TLS 1.3, specifically ML-DSA and ML-KEM, as well as updates on Password Authenticated Key Exchange (PAKE) and a proposal for PQC rollback resistance. Key administrative updates included the resolution of an appeal regarding ML-KEM and the publication of several RFCs related to Encrypted Client Hello (ECH) and DTLS.

## Key Discussion Points

### WG Update
Joe Salowey provided an update on the status of the working group:
- **Appeal Status:** The appeal regarding the adoption of [draft-ietf-tls-mlkem](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-mlkem/) was unsuccessful; the document remains an adopted working group draft.
- **RFC Publications:** Several documents have recently been published as RFCs, including TLS ECH Bootstrapping, ECH DNS bindings, and DTLS 1.3.
- **Implementation Status:** For [draft-ietf-tls-super-jumbo-record-limit](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-super-jumbo-record-limit/), additional implementation experience is sought beyond the initial work by Hannes Tschofenig.
- **Presentation:** [TLS WG Update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-tls-sessb-tls-wg-update-00)

### Use of ML-DSA in TLS 1.3
Tim Hollebeek presented [draft-ietf-tls-mldsa](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-mldsa/).
- **Content:** The draft registers code points for the three ML-DSA sizes and prohibits their use in TLS 1.2 to maintain the policy of not backporting PQC to older protocol versions.
- **Discussion:** 
    - Richard Barnes questioned whether a standalone draft is necessary or if IANA registration referencing FIPS 204 would suffice.
    - David Benjamin and Tim Hollebeek argued that a document is necessary to specify technical details like context strings and interactions with X.509.
    - Victor Dukovny raised concerns about whether the TLS 1.2 prohibition affects certificate chains.
    - Eric Rescorla (EKR) noted that the normative language regarding the TLS 1.2 prohibition needs more technical precision to clarify its application to signature schemes versus certificate chains.
- **Presentation:** [Hollebeek - Use of ML-DSA in TLS 1.3](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-tls-hollebeek-use-of-ml-dsa-in-tls-13-00)

### TLS PAKE
Laura Shea presented an update on [draft-ietf-tls-pake](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-pake/).
- **Content:** Version 01 includes C-PACE specifications and minor clarifications. Formal analysis using ProVerif is underway to verify that TLS finished messages sufficiently replace explicit key confirmation.
- **Discussion:**
    - Scott Fluhrer highlighted a security consideration for Spake2+ where solving a single discrete log problem could compromise the system.
    - Osama Mazahir and Eric Rescorla emphasized that substantial formal analysis is a prerequisite for advancing this document, given the protocol changes involved.
    - Thomas Fossati clarified that the Formal Analysis Team (FAT) serves as an advisor to the chairs and working group rather than a formal gatekeeper for consensus.
- **Presentation:** [TLS PAKE](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-tls-sessb-tls-pake-00)

### ML-KEM for TLS 1.3
Deirdre Chen presented [draft-ietf-tls-mlkem](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-mlkem/).
- **Content:** The draft describes an ML-KEM-only cipher suite (non-hybrid). Recent updates on GitHub include clarified security considerations regarding hybrid vs. KEM-only approaches and the prohibition of randomness/ciphertext reuse.
- **Discussion:**
    - Eric Rescorla requested a formal analysis of the previous Working Group Last Call (WGLC) results to determine the path forward.
    - Victor Dukovny suggested reframing security considerations to describe risks neutrally rather than labeling them as "proponent" views.
    - Osama Mazahir expressed strong opposition, arguing that the draft represents a security degradation compared to hybrid schemes and that the work should have originated in the CFRG.
    - John Mattsson raised concerns regarding privacy and static key requirements in FIPS 203 and SP 800-227.
- **Presentation:** [ML-KEM for TLS 1.3](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-tls-ml-kem-for-tls-13-00)

### PQC Continuity
Yaron Sheffer presented a non-working group draft concerning PQC rollback resistance.
- **Content:** The proposal utilizes a TOFU (Trust On First Use) mechanism where servers signal their commitment to support PQC certificates, allowing clients to detect "downgrade" attacks by a quantum-capable middlebox.
- **Discussion:**
    - Eric Rescorla inquired about implementation interest from major entities.
    - The discussion focused on how this compares to HSTS-based or PKI-based solutions.
- **Presentation:** [PQC Continuity](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-tls-pqc-continuity-00)

## Decisions and Action Items

1.  **[draft-ietf-tls-mldsa](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-mldsa/):** Authors (Tim Hollebeek) will work with Eric Rescorla and others to refine the normative text regarding the TLS 1.2 prohibition before initiating WGLC.
2.  **[draft-ietf-tls-mlkem](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-mlkem/):** The Chairs (Joe Salowey and Deirdre Chen) will provide a formal summary of the previous WGLC consensus and an analysis of the way forward.
3.  **[draft-ietf-tls-pake](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-pake/):** Authors will continue the formal analysis using ProVerif. Scott Fluhrer to provide text for the discrete log security consideration.
4.  **Implementation Check:** The WG is seeking additional implementations for [draft-ietf-tls-super-jumbo-record-limit](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-tls-super-jumbo-record-limit/).

